{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412774"},"attributes":{"position":7,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.71,0.12,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49086"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13484"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49086"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a high-speed motor vehicle accident. She sustains blunt intra-abdominal injury requiring emergency surgery. Additionally, several hairline rib fractures are identified on the left side. Apart from some tenderness over her ribs, there is no evidence of serious chest injury on X-ray. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo days after her abdominal surgery, she complains of breathlessness. The operation itself had been uneventful and she had been making good post-operative progress up to this stage. She has been using opioid analgesia for pain control over the past few days. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Aside from scattered crackles at both lung bases, the lung fields are otherwise clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumothorax","Basal atelectasis","Pulmonary embolus","Opioid over-use","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is likely suffering a post-operative pulmonary complication, as indicated by her increasing dyspnoea, mild fever, and auscultatory findings. The time to symptom presentation is often used to narrow down the differential diagnoses in the perioperative period. At 24-72 hours post-op, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal atelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs soon after induction of general anaesthesia. Following surgery, patient movement and breathing are often limited by pain, which inhibits appropriate re-expansion of the lung. This, in turn, can lead to the development of pneumonia, typically occurring around day three to five post-op.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration given the patient\u0027s recent rib fractures. However, it is less likely as there were no signs at the primary examination, and the patient had been well leading up to this stage. Additionally, her oxygen saturation is well-maintained.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolus\u003C/strong\u003E is considered a late complication and typically presents with sudden onset dyspnoea with associated chest pain around seven days post-op. The patient\u0027s vital signs are also not consistent with pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid over-use\u003C/strong\u003E can cause respiratory depression, which may present with breathlessness. However, this patient\u0027s respiratory rate is normal, and she appears well, making opioid-induced respiratory depression less likely. Nevertheless, opioid use should be monitored closely in the post-operative period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops later in the post-operative course (around day three to five) and would likely present with more significant fever and respiratory symptoms. While it remains a possibility, basal atelectasis is more likely at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-operative pulmonary atelectasis is common and usually responds to simple physiotherapy exercises.","Rib fractures and post-operative pain can contribute to the development of atelectasis by limiting chest wall movement."],"references":["Platell C, Hall JC. Atelectasis after Abdominal Surgery. J Am Coll Surg. 1997;185(6):584-592. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9404885/","Kelkar KV. Post-operative pulmonary complications after non-cardiothoracic surgery. Indian J Anaesth. 2015;59(9):599-605. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4613407/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T16:01:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:34:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49086"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"a